South Africa Stocks Fall 1st Day in 4, Led by BHP Billiton, Anglo American

-- B y   C a r l i   L o u r e n s
-- 
2011-03-25T16:17:23Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-25/south-africa-stocks-fall-1st-day-in-4-led-by-bhp-billiton-anglo-american.html
South Africa ’s FTSE/JSE  Africa  All
Share Index snapped three days of gains, dropping 51.8, or 0.2
percent, to 31,595.89 by the 5 p.m. close in Johannesburg.  The following are among the most active stocks in the South
African market today.  AngloGold Ashanti Ltd. (ANG)  , the world’s third-largest
gold producer, fell 4.50 rand, or 1.4 percent, to 321.50 rand.
Gold imports by  India , the world’s biggest consumer, may plunge
for a second month in March as price swings deter buyers, the
Bombay Bullion Association said. Gold holdings in the SPDR Gold
Trust, the biggest exchange-traded fund backed by bullion,
decreased 0.91 metric tons to 1,213.96 metric tons as of March
24, according to figures on the company’s website.  Gold Fields
Ltd. (GFI) , Africa’s second largest producer of the metal after
AngloGold, lost 3.20 rand, or 2.7 percent, to 116.50 rand.  BHP Billiton Plc (BIL)  , the world’s largest mining
company, reversed two days of gains, falling 2.34 cents, or 0.9
percent, to 260.20 rand. Lead, copper and zinc prices declined
on the London Metals Exchange.  Anglo American Plc (AGL)  , the
diversified mining company that makes up 11 percent of South
Africa’s benchmark stock index, declined 83 cents, or 0.2
percent, to 355 rand.  South African Coal Mining Holdings Ltd. (SAH)  , the
producer of the fuel, more than doubled to 1 rand as it resumed
trading after being suspended early in 2009 because annual
financial results weren’t released by the required date. The
shares last traded at 41 cents apiece on May 4, 2009, according
to Bloomberg data.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Carli Lourens in Johannesburg at 
 clourens@bloomberg.net   To contact the editors responsible for this story:
